Initial codebase :
I built my codebase from scratch in Python rather than adopting a full Bayesian-optimisation library. The surrogate modelling uses functions from scikit-learn (GaussianProcessRegressor and SVR) with SciPy for the acquisition optimisation, but the optimisation loop, the diagnostics, and all of the decision logic are my own. This was a deliberate choice for this project. A black-box library can only hand me a recommendation each round without teaching the process behind the decisions. However, the entire value of the capstone is in seeing and understanding the mechanics of how the kernel, the length scales, the acquisition function, and the model's own uncertainty actually arrive at a query point conclusion. A transparent, lightweight pipeline also lets me perform per-function diagnostics and hand-written heuristics that an off-the-shelf optimiser does not expose.
The repository is organised with one folder per function, each holding the query pipeline, a k-means characterisation notebook, plus shared DATASHEET.md, and MODELCARD.md artefacts
